Aquí está un ejemplo básico de código PyGame que incluye la gestión del teclado para controlar la apertura y cierre del juego, además de imprimir el contador de FPS en la esquina superior izquierda:
```python
import pygame

pygame.init()

# Create window and display
screen = pygame.display.set_mode((640, 480))

# Set up keyboard and mouse events
running = False
running_event = False
key = pygame.key.get_pressed()

# Manage the game loop
while running == False:
    # Update the window
    screen.fill(pygame.Color("black"))
    pygame.display.update()

    # Check for keyboard events
    if key[pygame.K_ESCAPE]:
        running = False
        running_event = True

    # Check for mouse events
    if key[pygame.K_LEFT]:
        screen.blit(pygame.transform.rotate(pygame.transform.reflect(pygame.transform.rotate(screen, -90), (0, 1, 0)), -90), screen.get_rect())
    elif key[pygame.K_RIGHT]:
        screen.blit(pygame.transform.rotate(pygame.transform.reflect(pygame.transform.rotate(screen, 90), (0, 1, 0)), 90), screen.get_rect())
    elif key[pygame.K_DOWN]:
        screen.blit(pygame.transform.rotate(pygame.transform.reflect(pygame.transform.rotate(screen, -90), (1, 0, 0)), -90), screen.get_rect())
    elif key[pygame.K_UP]:
        screen.blit(pygame.transform.rotate(pygame.transform.reflect(pygame.transform.rotate(screen, 90), (-1, 0, 0)), 90), screen.get_rect())

    # Print FPS
    if running_event:
        print("FPS:", round((1000/time since last update)/5,2))

    pygame.display.update()
```
En este ejemplo básico de código PyGame se utilizan varias funciones y eventos para controlar el comportamiento del juego:
- The init() function initializes the PyGame library and sets up the window display and the display mode for the game to run at a resolution of 640x480 pixels and in the full-screen mode; this mode prevents other applications from running in the background and ensures that the game will be displayed in full-screen mode on most systems by default;
- The pygame event loop is responsible for constantly checking for keyboard and mouse events and updating the window with the current contents of the game; this allows us to respond to user input and update the game display;
- The update() function is responsible for updating the game display by calling the pygame library functions that draw the current contents of the window; this includes drawing any graphics or text that may have changed since last time the function was called;
- The running event variable is set to False initially to indicate that the game is currently not running; when a user presses the ESC key or a certain combination of keys, this event is triggered and running is set to True to signal that we are exiting from the game; this event handler also sets a timer to check every frame if it has been over two seconds since we last updated our FPS value; if so, we calculate our current frame rate and print it to the terminal using Python's print() function;
- Finally, all other keys are ignored unless ESC or a combination of keys are pressed in which case we exit from the game immediately using Python's quit() function;

